  "why": "The paper's method, TACTIC, enforces both semantic consistency and naturalness across its search iterations, aligning with the 'High' rating. \n1. Naturalness: The method's core is an image-to-image translation model (MUNIT) trained on real-world images of various environmental conditions (e.g., rain, snow). This model learns a 'style space' that represents a plausible distribution of these conditions. The search for failure-inducing inputs is conducted within this learned latent style space, inherently constraining the generated images to be realistic and natural-looking. The paper explicitly validates this through a user study, demonstrating the superior realism of its generated scenes compared to other methods.\n2. Semantic Consistency: The test oracle is a metamorphic relation that compares the steering angle of an original scene to its transformed version, assuming the underlying road geometry and driving task remain consistent. The MUNIT architecture is specifically designed to enforce this by separating an image's 'content' (e.g., road shape) from its 'style' (e.g., weather). By preserving the content vector of the original image and only swapping the style vector, the method ensures semantic consistency, making the metamorphic oracle valid.\n3. Prevention of Cumulative Distortion: The search algorithm ((1+1) Evolution Strategy) mutates a style vector in the latent space, not the image itself. For each fitness evaluation, this style vector is applied to the original, unmodified seed images. This process prevents the cumulative distortion or 'drift' that can occur when mutations are applied iteratively to already-mutated images. The perturbation is always controlled relative to the original seed data.",
  "evidence": "Page 2, Section 1: \"To specify the environmental conditions of an environmental type, instead of using configurations, TACTIC employs the Multimodal Unsupervised Image-to-Image Translation (MUNIT) to deep-learn the features of environmental conditions from a set of sample scenes belonging to the same environmental type and encode them as a high-dimensional vector space called style space.\"\n\nPage 4, Section 3.1: \"MUNIT is that the representation of images can be decomposed into a content space that is domain-invariant and a style space that captures domain-specific characteristics... the domain-invariant content space will encode the information shared by scenes of the two different environmental types, such as the road information like the shapes of road and the roadside trees.\"\n\nPage 5, Section 3.2.2: \"Following the existing work (Tian et al., 2018), we also adopt Metamorphic Relation (MR) (Chen et al., 2020) as the test oracle... In particular, the MR used in TACTIC is defined as that the steering angles should be consistent among the driving scenes transformed from the same ones by applying different style vectors, i.e., retain behaviour consistency.\"\n\nPage 6, Section 3.2.3: The fitness function for detecting erroneous behaviours, `Fa(s) = 1/|Io| * Σ_{x∈Io} |f(x) – f(g(x, s))|`, demonstrates that for each style vector `s` being evaluated, the transformation `g` is applied to the original images `x` from the original dataset `Io`, thus preventing cumulative distortion."
